          "body": "Joshua 4 is fundamentally a chapter about how God engineers human memory of His acts. He does not leave remembrance to chance or to natural human tendencies — He commissions a specific physical object (twelve stones), a specific location (Gilgal), and a specific liturgical conversation (child's question, parent's theologically prescribed answer). The entire apparatus is God-designed, God-commanded, and God-interpreted. This reveals something essential about the nature of divine grace: God does not only act in history; He also ensures the meaning of His acts is correctly transmitted. The miracle without the memorial would be a story lost in two generations. The memorial without the miracle would be an empty monument. Together they are a covenant memory-system."
